Let $H$ be the orthocenter of $\triangle ABC$, and let $O$ be the circumcenter of $\triangle ABC$.

Since $\angle BAC = 60^\circ$, triangle $BOC$ is equilateral.  Then $OB = OC$, so $O$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of $\overline{BC}$.  Also, $HB = HC$, so $H$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of $\overline{BC}$.  Therefore, line $HO$ is the perpendicular bisector of $\overline{BC}$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, H, O, X;

B = (0,0);
C = (10,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc(B,sqrt(73),0,180),arc(C,7,0,180));
H = orthocenter(A,B,C);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);
X = extension(B,C,O,H);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(O--H);
draw(A--H);
draw(rightanglemark(O,foot(O,B,C),B,20));

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$H$", H, NE);
label("$O$", O, NW);
label("$X$", X, S);
[/asy]

Since $H$ is the orthocenter of $\triangle ABC$, $\angle BHA = 90^\circ - \angle ABC = \angle ACB$.  Also, $\angle BXA = \angle CXA$, so triangles $BXH$ and $CXA$ are similar.  Therefore, $\frac{BX}{CX} = \frac{BH}{CA}$.

