Suppose Alice removes $2n - 1$ cards, leaving $2001 - 2n$ cards. Imagine these cards laid out in a row.  Then there are $2002 - 2n$ spaces to place the $2n - 1$ cards Alice removed (including the spaces at the ends of the row).

In order for Cheshire to lose, no $n$ consecutive cards from the original deck can be together.  This means that in our arrangement of cards, no two cards removed by Alice can be adjacent.  The number of ways to choose $2n - 1$ spaces out of $2002 - 2n$ is
\[\binom{2002 - 2n}{2n - 1}.\]The total number of ways to choose $2n - 1$ spaces out of $2002 - 2n$ without restriction is
\[\binom{2002 - 2n}{2n - 1}.\]Therefore, the probability that Cheshire loses is
\[\frac{\binom{2002 - 4n + 1}{2n - 1}}{\binom{2002 - 2n}{2n - 1}}.\]We want to maximize this expression.  We can write
\begin{align*}
\frac{\binom{2002 - 4n + 1}{2n - 1}}{\binom{2002 - 2n}{2n - 1}} &= \frac{(2002 - 4n + 1)!}{(2n - 1)!(1982 - 6n + 1)!} \cdot \frac{(2n - 1)!(1982 - 4n + 1)!}{(2002 - 2n)!} \\
&= \frac{(2002 - 4n + 1)(2002 - 4n)(2002 - 4n - 1) \dotsm (1983 - 4n)}{(2002 - 2n)(2002 - 2n - 1)(2002 - 2n - 2) \dotsm (1983 - 2n)}.
