\[\frac{a_{n + 1}}{a_n} = \frac{(1982 - 4n)(1981 - 4n)}{(2001 - 2n)(2000 - 2n)}.\]This is less than 1 if and only if
\[(1982 - 4n)(1981 - 4n) < (2001 - 2n)(2000 - 2n).\]This simplifies to $n^2 - 999n + 99000 > 0,$ which factors as $(n - 110)(n - 900) > 0.$  Thus, $\frac{a_{n + 1}}{a_n} < 1$ for $n \ge 901,$ so the sequence $\{a_n\}$ is decreasing for $n \ge 901.$  Also, $\frac{a_{n + 1}}{a_n} > 1$ for $n \le 899,$ so the sequence $\{a_n\}$ is increasing for $n \le 899.$  Therefore, $a_n$ is maximized at $n = \boxed{900}.$  (We can check that $a_{900} > a_{901}.$)

