\[\frac{k}{1 - k} < n.\]Also, $0 \le r$ implies that $n - k \ge 0,$ so
\[n \ge k.\]For each positive integer $n,$ the set of $x$ such that $\lfloor x \rfloor = n$ which satisfy the given equation correspond to values of $k$ such that
\[\frac{k}{1 - k} < n \le \frac{k}{1 - k} + 1.\]Thus, for each positive integer $n,$ there is an interval of length
\[\left( \frac{k}{1 - k} + 1 \right) - \frac{k}{1 - k} = 1\]containing the values of $k$ which produce one solution $x$ with $\lfloor x \rfloor = n.$

