We use complementary probability.  That is, we compute the probability that Cheshire *doesn't* win, and subtract from 1.

Suppose Alice removes $2n - 1$ cards such that no $n$ are consecutive.  Imagine the remaining $2001 - 2n$ cards in a row.  The $2n - 1$ removed cards must be in the $2001 - 2n + 1 = 2002 - 2n$ spaces created by these cards (including the spaces at the ends).

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

int i;

draw((0,0)--(12,0));

for (i = 0; i <= 12; ++i) {
  draw((i,-0.2)--(i,0.2));
}

