label("$2$", (1,-0.2), S);
label("$3$", (2,-0.2), S);
label("$\dots$", (5,0), S);
label("$2001 - 2n$", (11,-0.2), S);
label("$2002 - 2n$", (12,-0.2), S);
[/asy]

Furthermore, no two of these removed cards can be in the same space, or else there would be $n$ consecutive cards left.  Thus, we must choose $2n - 1$ of the $2002 - 2n$ spaces.  This can be done in $\binom{2002 - 2n}{2n - 1}$ ways.

There are $\binom{2000}{2n - 1}$ ways to choose $2n - 1$ cards out of 2000, so the probability that Cheshire doesn't win is
\[\frac{\binom{2002 - 2n}{2n - 1}}{\binom{2000}{2n - 1}} = \frac{(2002 - 2n)(2001 - 2n) \dotsm (1804 - 2n)}{(2000)(1999) \dotsm (1802)}.\]We want to find the largest $n$ such that this fraction is greater than or equal to $\frac{1}{2}.$

We see that the fraction is less than 1, and each time we increase $n$ by 1, the fraction is multiplied by
\[\frac{(1802 - 2n)(1803 - 2n)}{(2001 - 2n)(2002 - 2n)}.\]This fraction is less than 1, so the fractions are decreasing.  We want to find the first time this fraction is less than $\frac{1}{2}.$

We compute that for $n = 667,$
\[\frac{(2002 - 2n)(2001 - 2n) \dotsm (1804 - 2n)}{(2000)(1999) \dotsm (1802)} = \frac{668 \cdot 667 \dotsm 1}{2000 \cdot 1999 \dotsm 1334} < \frac{1}{2},\]so the largest such $n$ is 666.  Alice should choose $n = \boxed{666}.$

