Let $n = \lfloor x \rfloor.$  Then $x = n + \{x\},$ so
\[n \{x\} = k(n + \{x\}).\]This simplifies to $(n - k) \{x\} = kn.$

If $n = k,$ then $kn = 0,$ so $k = n = 0,$ which is not possible.  Thus, $n - k \neq 0,$ so
\[\{x\} = \frac{kn}{n - k}.\]Since $0 \le \{x\} < 1,$
\[0 \le \frac{kn}{n - k} < 1.\]We can write
\[0 \le \frac{k}{1 - k/n} < 1.\]Since $k > 0$ and $n$ is an integer, $1 - k/n > 0.$  Hence,
\[0 \le k < 1 - \frac{k}{n}.\]Then $k + \frac{k}{n} < 1,$ so
\[k < \frac{n}{n + 1}.\]For a fixed positive integer $n,$ the equation
\[\{x\} = \frac{kn}{n - k}\]has a unique solution in $x$ if and only if $0 < k < \frac{n}{n + 1}.$

