\[0 \le \frac{kn}{n - k} < 1.\]The left inequality is always true.  The right inequality becomes $kn < n - k,$ or $k(n + 1) < n.$  Then
\[k < \frac{n}{n + 1}.\]If $n < k,$ then
\[0 \le \frac{kn}{n - k} < 1.\]The right inequality is always true.  The left inequality becomes $kn > 0,$ so $n > 0.$  Also, $k(n + 1) > n.$  Then
\[k > \frac{n}{n + 1}.\]Thus, for a fixed positive integer $n,$ the solutions in $x$ correspond to values of $k$ such that
\[k \in \left( \frac{n}{n + 1}, \infty \right) \setminus \{n\}\]if $n = 1,$ and
