The altitude has length $4$, and it is the longer leg of the 30-60-90 triangle.  Therefore, the shorter leg has length $4/\sqrt{3} = 4\sqrt{3}/3$, and the side length of the equilateral triangle is $s = 8\sqrt{3}/3$.

**Expressing the Desired Quantity**

We want to find $|x + 2y + 3z|^2$.  Notice that we can rewrite this as:

 $$|x+2y+3z|^2 = |(-x) + 2(-y) + 3z|^2$$

The quantity inside the magnitude on the right-hand side represents the vector sum:

$$-1(-x) - 2(-y) + 3z$$

This is a linear combination of the vectors representing the points $-x$, $-y$, and $z$.

**Geometric Visualization of the Linear Combination**

Imagine starting at the origin.  We go one unit in the direction opposite to $-x$, then two units in the direction opposite to $-y$, and finally three units in the direction of $z$.  This is equivalent to starting at $-x$, going twice the length of a side of the equilateral triangle to a point $P$, and then moving three times the length of a side in the direction of $z$ to the final point $Q$.

