We consider the probability that Cheshire **loses**. This occurs when there are no $n$ consecutive integers among the $2n-1$ cards Cheshire receives. 

Imagine the $2000- (2n-1) = 2001-2n$ cards Cheshire *doesn't* receive.  These cards, along with the gaps at the beginning and end of the deck, form $2002-2n$ slots into which Cheshire's cards could be placed (without affecting whether or not Cheshire wins).

