Since $|x+z|=|y+z|=|x-y|$, the points $x$, $y$, $-z$ form an equilateral triangle.  Let $O$ be the center of this triangle.  Then $O$ is also the centroid of triangle $xyz$.

The centroid of a triangle divides each median in the ratio $2:1$.  Therefore,
\[O = \frac{x + y + (-z)}{3} = \frac{x + y - z}{3},\]so $x + y - z = 3O$.  Then
\begin{align*}
|x + 2y + 3z|^2 &= |(x + y - z) + (y + 4z)|^2 \\
&= |3O + (y + 4z)|^2.
\end{align*}Since $O$ is the centroid of triangle $xyz$,
\[O = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{y + z}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \cdot x = \frac{x + y + z}{3},\]so $y + z = 3O - x$.  Then
\[y + 4z = (y + z) + 3z = (3O - x) + 3z = 3(O + z) - x.\]Hence,
\begin{align*}
|x + 2y + 3z|^2 &= |3O + (y + 4z)|^2 \\
&= |3O + 3(O + z) - x|^2 \\
&= |6O + 3z - x|^2 \\
&= |3(2O + z) - x|^2.
\end{align*}Since $O$ is the center of equilateral triangle $xyz$, $2O + z = -x$, so
\[|x + 2y + 3z|^2 = |-3x - x|^2 = |-4x|^2 = 16 |x|^2.\]Since $x$, $y$, $-z$ form an equilateral triangle with side length 4, the distance from a vertex to the centroid is $\frac{2}{3} \cdot 4 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = \frac{4 \sqrt{3}}{3}$.  Therefore, $|x| = \frac{4 \sqrt{3}}{3}$, so
\[|x + 2y + 3z|^2 = 16 |x|^2 = 16 \cdot \frac{48}{9} = \boxed{85}.\]

