\[OM = \sqrt{AO^2 - AM^2} = \sqrt{100 - r^2}.\]Then $CM = CO - OM = \sqrt{r^2 + 100} - \sqrt{100 - r^2}$.

Since $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, $\overline{CM}$ is an altitude.  By the Pythagorean Theorem on $\triangle ACM$,
\[(r + s)^2 = AC^2 = AM^2 + CM^2 = r^2 + \left( \sqrt{r^2 + 100} - \sqrt{100 - r^2} \right)^2.\]This simplifies to $2rs + s^2 = 200 - 2 \sqrt{(r^2 + 100)(100 - r^2)}$.  Then
\[s^2 + 2rs + 2 \sqrt{(r^2 + 100)(100 - r^2)} - 200 = 0.\]We can view this as a quadratic in $s$.  By the quadratic formula,
\[s = \frac{-2r \pm \sqrt{4r^2 - 4 \cdot 2 \sqrt{(r^2 + 100)(100 - r^2)} + 800}}{2} = -r \pm \sqrt{r^2 - 2 \sqrt{(r^2 + 100)(100 - r^2)} + 200}.\]Since $s$ is positive,
\begin{align*}
s &= -r + \sqrt{r^2 - 2 \sqrt{(r^2 + 100)(100 - r^2)} + 200} \\
&= -r + \sqrt{(r^2 + 100) + (100 - r^2) - 2 \sqrt{(r^2 + 100)(100 - r^2)}} \\
&= -r + \sqrt{(\sqrt{r^2 + 100} - \sqrt{100 - r^2})^2} \\
&= -r + \sqrt{r^2 + 100} - \sqrt{100 - r^2}.
\end{align*}Then the area of $\gamma_3$ is
\[\pi s^2 = \pi \left( -r + \sqrt{r^2 + 100} - \sqrt{100 - r^2} \right)^2.\]To maximize this, we want to maximize $-r + \sqrt{r^2 + 100} - \sqrt{100 - r^2}$.

Let $x = \sqrt{r^2 + 100}$ and $y = \sqrt{100 - r^2}$.  Then $x^2 + y^2 = 200$, and we want to maximize
\[-r + x - y = -\sqrt{x^2 - 100} + x - y.\]By Cauchy-Schwarz,
\[(1^2 + 1^2)(x^2 + y^2) \ge (x + y)^2,\]so $x + y \le \sqrt{400} = 20$.  Equality occurs when $x = y = 10$, or $r = 0$.  This is not possible, so $x + y < 20$.

