Thus, $x$, $y$, and $-z$ form the vertices of an equilateral triangle with side length 4.  Let $\omega$ be a complex cube root of unity; then rotating $x - (-z)$ by $120^\circ$ counterclockwise about $-z$ gives us $y - (-z),$ so
\[y - (-z) = \omega [x - (-z)].\]Then $y = \omega x + (1 - \omega) z.$  Hence,
\begin{align*}
|x + 2y + 3z|^2 &= |x + 2 [\omega x + (1 - \omega) z] + 3z|^2 \\
&= |(1 + 2 \omega) x + (3 - 2 \omega) z|^2.
\end{align*}Since $|1 + 2 \omega| = |3 - 2 \omega|$ and $\frac{3 - 2 \omega}{1 + 2 \omega}$ is a cube root of unity (and hence has absolute value 1),
\begin{align*}
|(1 + 2 \omega) x + (3 - 2 \omega) z|^2 &= |1 + 2 \omega|^2 |x + z|^2 \\
&= |1 + 2 \omega|^2 \cdot 4^2 \\
&= (1 + 4 \cos 120^\circ + 4)(16) \\
&= \boxed{48}.
\end{align*}

